    "summary": "The reign of Septimius Severus (193–211 AD) marked a significant turning point in the [[event:81|Roman Empire's]] history — the rise of the first emperor from Africa (born in Leptis Magna, modern Libya) and the beginning of the Severan dynasty, which transformed the empire's political character by further militarizing the government and increasing the army's political role. Severus came to power during the [[event:2814|Year of the Five Emperors]] (193 AD) following Commodus's assassination, defeating his rivals in civil war and establishing firm control. His famous deathbed advice to his sons: 'Enrich the soldiers, ignore everyone else.'\n\nSeverus's reign represented both success and ominous portent. He successfully campaigned in the east (sacking Ctesiphon and creating two new eastern provinces), campaigned in Britain (dying at York in 211 AD while campaigning in Scotland), and maintained military discipline. But his elevation of soldiers' pay and status at the expense of the Senate accelerated the militarization of imperial politics that would culminate in the [[event:2025|Crisis of the Third Century]]. The Severan dynasty ended badly: his sons Caracalla and Geta co-ruled briefly before Caracalla murdered Geta, and after Caracalla's assassination the dynasty lurched through chaos. However, [[event:2853|Caracalla's Constitutio Antoniniana]] (extending citizenship to virtually all free inhabitants of the empire) was the most significant legal act of the Severan period.",
